Best Initial Use Cases
Holster Memory is strongest in domains where access patterns are predictable and the value of “runs at all” is high.
Local LLM inference
•	model layers are sequential
•	weights are reused in known patterns
•	prefetching can be effective
•	avoiding OOM is extremely valuable
Image generation and diffusion workflows
•	staged blocks and predictable steps
•	repeated operations across passes
•	large models benefit from capacity more than perfect latency
Creative and scene-heavy workflows
•	assets can remain loaded in a passive tier
•	active viewport or working set stays in VRAM
•	avoids full reload behavior and hard memory walls
Scientific and batch compute
•	many jobs tolerate some latency increase
•	predictable staging is possible
•	throughput and capacity are often more important than interactive smoothness
________________________________________
What Holster Memory Is Not
Holster Memory is not a claim that slower memory can equal VRAM speed.
It does not promise:
•	zero slowdown
•	universal gains in all workloads
•	benchmark-leading gaming performance
•	magic pooling that ignores bandwidth limits
It does promise a different memory philosophy:
•	keep the full workload alive somewhere nearby
•	keep the active set in fast VRAM
•	prefetch intelligently
•	degrade gracefully instead of failing outright
________________________________________
Why AI Is a Strong Fit
AI workloads are unusually compatible with staged memory systems because they often have predictable structure.
Common characteristics include:
•	layer-by-layer execution
•	repeated reuse of weights
•	known upcoming operations
•	chunkable computation
That makes it possible to predict what should be active next.
When the system can pre-position upcoming data into VRAM before it is needed, the performance penalty of the slower passive tier becomes manageable.
In this setting, more memory at somewhat lower speed can be far more useful than insufficient fast memory.
