Design Principles
A Holster Memory runtime should follow a few core principles:
1. The GPU should never be surprised
If needed data is missing from VRAM at the moment of execution, the user feels the stall.
2. VRAM is a cache, not a warehouse
VRAM should hold what is hot, not everything.
3. Promotion matters more than raw capacity
The right data in VRAM at the right time matters more than blindly increasing memory size.
4. Graceful degradation beats hard failure
A slower-running model is often more valuable than a model that refuses to load.
5. Predictability beats guesswork
Rules for promotion, demotion, and pinning should be explicit and measurable.
________________________________________
Scheduler Responsibilities
The scheduler is the brain of the system. Its job is to manage movement, not computation.
Core responsibilities:
•	identify hot vs cold data
•	reserve VRAM for the active set
•	prefetch likely-needed chunks
•	demote cooling data back to the passive pool
•	pin critical buffers that must not be evicted
•	overlap transfers with compute whenever possible
Possible controls:
•	prefetch depth
•	reserved VRAM floor
•	pinned buffer budget
•	promotion aggressiveness
•	eviction policy
________________________________________
Metrics That Matter
A useful prototype should measure whether Holster Memory is actually helping.
Key metrics:
•	out-of-memory avoided vs baseline
•	total model size supported
•	time spent computing vs time spent waiting
•	transfer latency hidden by overlap
•	VRAM hit rate
•	promotion and eviction frequency
•	tokens per second or workload throughput
•	stutter or stall frequency
The first success condition is simple:
Does the workload run when it otherwise would not?
The second is:
Does it do so with acceptable slowdown?
________________________________________
Why This Is Legitimate
Holster Memory is not a fantasy concept. It is a consumer-oriented expression of ideas that already exist in fragments across computing:
•	CPU cache hierarchies
•	memory paging
•	texture streaming
•	unified memory systems
•	managed GPU memory
•	staged execution in AI runtimes
The novelty is not inventing memory tiers from nothing. The novelty is applying a clear, intentional tiered model to consumer GPU workloads and framing VRAM as an active execution cache rather than a fixed all-or-nothing container.
That makes this a systems architecture idea, not a science-fiction one.
________________________________________
Product Thesis
Holster Memory should not be introduced as a gaming benchmark feature. It should be introduced as a capability unlock.
Its first promise is not:
•	“your FPS will go up”
Its first promise is:
•	“your workload fits now”
•	“your local model can run now”
•	“your machine can do more with the hardware it already has”
That is a much stronger beachhead.
